<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06136357 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06136357 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photos (5); COVER PHOTO: Rick E. Martin -- Mercury News; TAKING THE FIELD;James Arthor, followed by his wife Kathy, carries his daughter Karen, 7months, to the softball field in Fremont's Central Park where he participatesin adult league softball. Softball, which provides a slice of baseball tomany, continues to rise in popularity. (color); PHOTOGRAPHS BY RICK E. MARTIN;Brian Bretz, above, keeps warm in his sleeping bag while Cindy Tanner, DaveGerds and Dale Gerds await their turns at snack bar.; PHOTO: At right, Al Auerdives for a grounder that got away.; PHOTO:; Carl Hinneschiedt watches hisfather play from perch behind backstop; PHOTO:; Ron Falcon, left, Sean Burkeand Al McKay watch tensely as their team goes to bat  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  ADULT; SOFTBALL; FREMONT  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  For a few, it offers the opportunity to live out a childhood dream. Heck,maybe even an adult dream.;    It gives the chance to feel the sameexhilaration that Jose Canseco might get from hitting a ball over the fenceand scoring the game-winning run. It also gives the former speed merchant achance to score from second base on a shallow single, much like RickeyHenderson might attempt.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  The Weekly, Part 2  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  SOFTBALL KEEPS DIAMOND DREAMS ALIVESPORT'S POPULARITY CONTINUES ON THE UPSWINGIN FREMONT  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     While the players know they are not on national television withoutmillion-dollar bank accounts, the game remains the common denominator.;   Softball, which -- for some -- provides a slice of baseball for thenot-so-gifted, continues to rise in popularity. In Fremont as well as mostother places in the country.;    &quot;It's a way to get back to doing the thingswe were once able to do,&quot; said 47-year-old Joe Olmos, a 1962 graduate ofWashington High. &quot;I've been playing about 30 years and I tell the wife as longas my legs hold up, I'll keep coming back out here.&quot;;    Olmos, who said heplayed for Washington's baseball team back in the early '60s, was one ofseveral hundred men over 45 who wanted to play among people their own age. Thecity finally obliged two year ago and formed the 45-and-over league. TheVintage League meets on Thursday evenings.;    &quot;We've had an amazing amount ofgrowth since I began here in 1979,&quot; said Gary Pratt, recreation supervisor forthe city of Fremont. &quot;We're mostly getting professionals now, doctors andlawyers and those types. We're also getting local companies who sponsor theiremployees' teams. The amount of players has probably quadrupled in just over10 years.&quot;;    For players under 45, there are regular adult leagues, whichoccupy the six softball diamonds at Central Park in Fremont seven nights aweek. The facility, one of the premier ones in the area, has become a field ofdreams for nearly 8,000 who at one time may have aspired to play atCandlestick Park.;    &quot;Most everyone out here has kids,&quot; said Anthony Almaraz,of Fremont. &quot;This is one of the only ways to still have recreation and let thefamily join in. I plan on playing until I drop.&quot;;    While most of the playerswon't admit it, they drag their wives, girlfriends and relatives out, torelive their days of glory.;    The bleachers at Central Park, behindFremont's city hall, are normally filled with relatives, who have eitherwillingly or grudgingly made their way out the park.;    &quot;Since we moved outhere from Memphis last year, we've all been coming out to watch,&quot; said SandraPerry of Newark who, along with 2 1/2-month-old daughter Kristen, comes out towatch her husband, Kim. &quot;At the end of the season he's ready for the nextleague to start up. We play in a co-ed league together, also. It's almostaddictive.&quot;  </TEXT><BYLINE>  PEDRO GOMEZ, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Alameda County/AM  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jo